Everyday Code Writing

Use this skill for small, focused coding tasks.

This skill is for everyday code work: small chunks, usually one file or a few closely related files. It should help the agent write clean code without overthinking, overbuilding, or changing unrelated parts of the project.

This skill does not replace:

Frontend design
Planning and task breakdown
Test-driven development
Database design
Backup and restore
Large multi-file architecture work

If the task becomes large, touches many files, changes architecture, or requires a full feature plan, stop and use a broader planning or implementation workflow instead.

When to Use

Use this skill for:

Editing one file
Fixing one small bug
Adding one helper function
Cleaning up one messy function
Improving one component
Fixing one TypeScript error
Fixing one build error
Fixing one PostgreSQL query
Adding one small validation rule
Improving one small user interaction
Renaming unclear variables
Removing small duplication
Handling one loading, empty, or error state
Making a small behavior change

Use this when the task is clear, limited, and easy to verify.

If the task touches many unrelated files, use a comprehensive implementation skill instead.